WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.360
Hello, everyone.

00:00:06.360 --> 00:00:07.800
My name is David Maguire.

00:00:07.800 --> 00:00:10.640
I am a data scientist at DV01.

00:00:10.640 --> 00:00:17.480
We are a fintech startup, and we provide analytics for investors in fixed income.

00:00:17.480 --> 00:00:23.440
So something that I've heard a few times over my career is that R is bad for production.

00:00:23.440 --> 00:00:28.760
Sometimes engineers say, oh, this looks great, but let's put it in another language for production.

00:00:28.760 --> 00:00:35.119
They say R is ad hoc, it's for analysis, there's no package management.

00:00:35.119 --> 00:00:39.799
But today, I want to dispel some of those notions, and I want to show you that R is

00:00:39.799 --> 00:00:44.119
great for production.

00:00:44.119 --> 00:00:48.320
So first I'd like to talk a little bit about what I work on.

00:00:48.320 --> 00:00:53.279
So I work on Tapecracker, which is a web application that has a few components.

00:00:53.279 --> 00:00:59.040
There's a JavaScript frontend, there's a Scala backend, and then we have a machine

00:00:59.040 --> 00:01:04.080
learning microservice in R, which provides predictions that are used by the two other

00:01:04.080 --> 00:01:06.519
components of the application.

00:01:06.519 --> 00:01:09.360
And this application is used live by customers.

00:01:09.360 --> 00:01:11.000
They can get on at any time.

00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:13.320
They expect their results immediately.

00:01:13.320 --> 00:01:18.559
So there's very high requirements for availability and dependability.

00:01:18.559 --> 00:01:24.519
Our sales team demos this app live to clients, to prospective clients, so it has to work

00:01:24.519 --> 00:01:25.599
every time.

00:01:25.599 --> 00:01:28.519
If there's a failure, we could lose a prospective client.

00:01:28.519 --> 00:01:35.839
So this machine learning microservice has to be very robustly engineered to satisfy

00:01:35.839 --> 00:01:40.720
what our customers expect of us.

00:01:40.720 --> 00:01:47.820
So I'm going to tell you how can you raise an R microservice to thrive in the wild.

00:01:47.820 --> 00:01:53.099
So here we have our R microservice, this cute little giraffe.

00:01:53.099 --> 00:01:57.739
So the first thing we're going to do is we're going to put our R microservice through school.

00:01:57.739 --> 00:02:01.980
We're going to teach it what to do once we release it out into the wild.

00:02:01.980 --> 00:02:06.699
The end result of that is that once we release it into the wild, it can interact with other

00:02:06.699 --> 00:02:11.380
microservices, other applications written in different languages seamlessly and just

00:02:11.380 --> 00:02:13.820
have a fun time.

00:02:13.820 --> 00:02:15.860
So let's talk a little bit more concretely.

00:02:15.860 --> 00:02:18.419
What is an R microservice?

00:02:18.419 --> 00:02:23.339
So it's basically R code behind Plumber and Docker.

00:02:23.339 --> 00:02:28.820
So we take our R code, our machine learning model, and we put it behind a Plumber API.

00:02:28.820 --> 00:02:34.619
This allows any other application to hit our machine learning model, and it only has to

00:02:34.619 --> 00:02:37.740
provide the expected input, and it gets an output.

00:02:37.740 --> 00:02:43.500
So any other service doesn't need to know anything about the R language.

00:02:43.500 --> 00:02:47.979
And then we wrap around that Plumber API.

00:02:47.979 --> 00:02:50.179
We put it in a Docker package.

00:02:50.179 --> 00:02:52.259
This makes our API portable.

00:02:52.259 --> 00:02:59.220
So once it's in a Docker package or a Docker image, we can deploy it into the cloud in

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:04.059
a variety of destinations.

00:03:04.059 --> 00:03:11.979
So a little bit more concretely, in our circumstance at DV01, the microservice wild, this is our

00:03:11.979 --> 00:03:12.979
web application.

00:03:12.979 --> 00:03:15.179
This is what it looks like.

00:03:15.179 --> 00:03:20.259
It provides a lot of information that investors need to make decisions.

00:03:20.259 --> 00:03:22.300
And we have a JavaScript frontend.

00:03:22.300 --> 00:03:29.699
We have a Scala backend, and then behind that even, we have a data engineering pipeline

00:03:29.699 --> 00:03:30.699
in Scala.

00:03:30.699 --> 00:03:36.380
And we have our R machine learning microservice sits on top of that and is able to provide

00:03:36.380 --> 00:03:42.059
results to each of the components in that pipeline.

00:03:42.059 --> 00:03:50.100
So this is a great setup for a data scientist, because I can focus on what I'm good at, which

00:03:50.100 --> 00:03:54.300
is building models and building data science projects, and then the software engineers

00:03:54.300 --> 00:03:58.500
that I work with, they can build the end-to-end system.

00:03:58.500 --> 00:04:01.699
So very convenient.

00:04:01.699 --> 00:04:08.820
So in pursuit of building robust R deployments, I want to introduce three DevOps principles.

00:04:08.820 --> 00:04:14.860
The first is continuous integration, and that's where we build and test our packages.

00:04:14.860 --> 00:04:17.700
The second is continuous deployment.

00:04:17.700 --> 00:04:22.980
This is where we take our tested packages and release them into production systems.

00:04:22.980 --> 00:04:31.040
And then the third is cluster computing, which is a common destination for applications in

00:04:31.040 --> 00:04:33.959
production in the cloud.

00:04:33.959 --> 00:04:37.079
So let's start with continuous integration.

00:04:37.079 --> 00:04:40.679
This is a simple continuous integration workflow.

00:04:40.679 --> 00:04:46.239
So we start at the top left, where a data scientist is working in R, in RStudio, making

00:04:46.239 --> 00:04:48.920
updates to the model, making updates to the code.

00:04:48.920 --> 00:04:56.000
So whenever a data scientist makes an update to the code base, they will push that to a

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:58.440
version tracking tool such as GitHub.

00:04:58.440 --> 00:05:04.480
At that point, the application will be built from the source code, and then we're going

00:05:04.480 --> 00:05:06.760
to run automated tests on that.

00:05:06.760 --> 00:05:08.600
And this happens automatically.

00:05:08.600 --> 00:05:12.399
Once I push, all that happens, and then I'll get a report back.

00:05:12.399 --> 00:05:16.279
If the tests fail, I know I have to go back and fix something.

00:05:16.279 --> 00:05:19.640
If the tests pass, I can then progress.

00:05:19.640 --> 00:05:27.399
I can merge my changes into the master brand, and then we will have an application that

00:05:27.399 --> 00:05:31.160
is ready for deployment.

00:05:31.160 --> 00:05:37.920
So let's look a little bit closer into this first part of the CI pipeline.

00:05:37.920 --> 00:05:43.959
So in the CI build step, basically we have data scientists working in RStudio, writing

00:05:43.959 --> 00:05:49.440
R code, and we are going to git push, and that's going to trigger GitHub actions to

00:05:49.440 --> 00:05:52.480
kick off the continuous integration pipeline.

00:05:52.480 --> 00:05:55.000
There's many options for CI tools.

00:05:55.000 --> 00:06:01.920
We use GitHub actions at DV01, and then the GitHub actions is going to build a Docker

00:06:01.920 --> 00:06:08.920
image based on the updated code, and what's important here is that I'm pushing my code

00:06:08.920 --> 00:06:10.160
frequently.

00:06:10.160 --> 00:06:15.920
That means that I can get instant feedback on what each piece of code that I edit, and

00:06:15.920 --> 00:06:17.440
so I know where changes happen.

00:06:17.440 --> 00:06:22.519
If I push 500 lines of code at once and something fails, it's going to take me a long time to

00:06:22.519 --> 00:06:26.920
figure out what goes wrong, but if I push a couple of lines at a time, I can isolate

00:06:26.920 --> 00:06:31.519
the problems very easily.

00:06:31.519 --> 00:06:33.399
So now let's look at this next step.

00:06:33.399 --> 00:06:36.799
We're running the automated tests.

00:06:36.799 --> 00:06:43.480
So within continuous integration tests, we have three broad categories of tests.

00:06:43.480 --> 00:06:45.239
Sort of there's this pyramid structure.

00:06:45.239 --> 00:06:47.160
The base are unit tests.

00:06:47.160 --> 00:06:50.760
These are the most numerous tests that we have.

00:06:50.760 --> 00:06:54.359
Of those, we have integration tests, which are still a good amount of those, but less

00:06:54.359 --> 00:07:01.799
than unit tests, and finally, there are end-to-end tests, and the test that package is very useful

00:07:01.799 --> 00:07:04.320
for writing these types of tests.

00:07:04.320 --> 00:07:11.239
So starting at unit tests, this is the base of our testing pyramid, and the goal here

00:07:11.239 --> 00:07:17.399
is to test functions, individual lines of code, and really look at each component of

00:07:17.399 --> 00:07:18.399
your R package.

00:07:18.399 --> 00:07:24.760
So here I have a trivial example of a unit test, where I define this add 20 function,

00:07:24.760 --> 00:07:31.440
and then I use test that to assert that if I add 20 to 10, it should equal 30, and I

00:07:31.440 --> 00:07:36.720
define this, and this is going to run every time I push updates to my package, so if I

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:41.040
were to make any changes to this function that would break it, I would get immediate

00:07:41.040 --> 00:07:48.119
feedback, and these type of tests are something that you should have a lot of.

00:07:48.119 --> 00:07:54.679
For example, it's a really good idea to create unit tests for your features to make sure

00:07:54.679 --> 00:08:01.160
that all the features that go into your models have tests and never break or never give unexpected

00:08:01.160 --> 00:08:02.160
input.

00:08:02.160 --> 00:08:10.000
If you're imputing missing values at prediction time, that would be a good thing to unit test.

00:08:10.000 --> 00:08:17.519
You could also test data structures, like make sure that functions return data frames

00:08:17.519 --> 00:08:22.359
of expected structures and things like that, so writing a lot of these unit tests allows

00:08:22.359 --> 00:08:27.399
you to make sure that your code doesn't break in unexpected ways, and it helps you identify

00:08:27.399 --> 00:08:30.399
failures.

00:08:30.399 --> 00:08:32.719
So the next level is integration tests.

00:08:32.719 --> 00:08:37.960
So for integration tests, the goal is to make sure that our microservice can interact with

00:08:37.960 --> 00:08:44.320
other services that it will need to, so we may be interacting with databases or APIs,

00:08:44.320 --> 00:08:49.599
so we're going to write tests to make sure that our R container can interact with every

00:08:49.599 --> 00:08:52.919
service it needs.

00:08:52.919 --> 00:08:57.520
And finally, there are end-to-end tests, and this is where we're looking at the whole microservices

00:08:57.520 --> 00:09:03.440
application as a whole, so this is, in our case, looking at our whole web app.

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:08.919
It doesn't really tell us much about our R microservice, but it's necessary to have a

00:09:08.919 --> 00:09:11.280
holistic view of everything.

00:09:11.280 --> 00:09:15.640
Where we actually get useful input about our R package are the two previous categories

00:09:15.640 --> 00:09:18.280
of tests.

00:09:18.280 --> 00:09:22.640
Now when we're writing tests, we want to write them at the right time.

00:09:22.640 --> 00:09:26.440
If you start writing tests too early, you can waste a lot of time, but they save a lot

00:09:26.440 --> 00:09:27.599
of time in production.

00:09:27.599 --> 00:09:32.799
So if you start a new project, when you're in the exploratory phase, doing EDA, initial

00:09:32.799 --> 00:09:37.080
experiments, if you start writing a lot of tests, you're going to slow yourself down.

00:09:37.080 --> 00:09:43.359
But as you progress, as you get your feature set more concrete, as you get closer to production,

00:09:43.359 --> 00:09:47.640
you should start introducing first unit tests, later integration tests, and once you're really

00:09:47.640 --> 00:09:53.919
close to production, to releasing a microservice, you're going to want to make sure that the

00:09:53.919 --> 00:10:00.159
end-to-end tests are properly configured.

00:10:00.159 --> 00:10:02.440
So next we're going to talk about continuous deployment.

00:10:03.239 --> 00:10:11.400
At the end of the continuous integration pipeline, we have our container that's ready for deployment.

00:10:11.400 --> 00:10:15.359
What is going to happen here is that this pipeline is going to take that container and

00:10:15.359 --> 00:10:19.840
it's going to push it through our different environment.

00:10:19.840 --> 00:10:24.400
Here at DVO1, we have a staging, release, and production environment.

00:10:24.400 --> 00:10:29.679
There's many ways to do continuous deployment, but this is just one example.

00:10:29.679 --> 00:10:36.919
So once the container is ready, it's going to be pushed to staging, and in staging, there

00:10:36.919 --> 00:10:41.719
will be some end-to-end tests that run, and we'll just make sure that the whole application

00:10:41.719 --> 00:10:43.919
looks good as a whole.

00:10:43.919 --> 00:10:49.520
If that goes well, it moves on to release, and then finally it will go to production.

00:10:49.520 --> 00:10:56.760
And this is important because we have a customer-facing application, and we have zero tolerance for

00:10:56.760 --> 00:10:58.719
any failures or for downtime.

00:10:58.760 --> 00:11:03.559
So we really need to make sure that we have a lot of steps in place to catch any errors

00:11:03.559 --> 00:11:05.960
that might come up.

00:11:05.960 --> 00:11:09.919
And each of these environments, the staging, release, and production, is a full replica

00:11:09.919 --> 00:11:11.640
of the production environment.

00:11:11.640 --> 00:11:17.880
It has our web application, it has the R microservice, as well as all the other services that make

00:11:17.880 --> 00:11:22.400
up the application.

00:11:22.400 --> 00:11:28.000
So let's talk a little bit about the last concept, which is cluster computing.

00:11:28.000 --> 00:11:32.960
So in the cloud, a common way to run jobs is in Kubernetes.

00:11:32.960 --> 00:11:38.479
So here we have our production cluster, in which we have three replicas of our machine

00:11:38.479 --> 00:11:39.479
learning application.

00:11:39.479 --> 00:11:44.119
So it's important that we're not just running it once, we're running it several times so

00:11:44.119 --> 00:11:46.320
we have redundancy.

00:11:46.320 --> 00:11:53.039
So when another microservice comes along and says, hey, R, give me some predictions, it's

00:11:53.039 --> 00:11:55.080
going to first go to a load balancer.

00:11:55.159 --> 00:11:59.359
The load balancer is going to look at all the replicas of our R machine learning microservice,

00:11:59.359 --> 00:12:06.559
and it's going to route it to one that is free and that is error-free.

00:12:06.559 --> 00:12:10.359
And then the R microservice will respond back.

00:12:10.359 --> 00:12:19.400
And then the full microservice application can continue doing its work.

00:12:19.400 --> 00:12:22.760
And so what's important here, as I mentioned, this is a replica set.

00:12:22.760 --> 00:12:28.840
So in Kubernetes, you have replica sets, which basically says that for this application,

00:12:28.840 --> 00:12:34.039
you're going to have always going to have three instances of this application in this

00:12:34.039 --> 00:12:36.159
case.

00:12:36.159 --> 00:12:42.080
And if one of the replicas goes bad, it will be torn down, and a new one will be spun up

00:12:42.080 --> 00:12:43.679
immediately.

00:12:43.679 --> 00:12:53.919
If we're getting high traffic, we can route new traffic to a free replica of our microservice.

00:12:53.919 --> 00:12:54.919
So it's very important.

00:12:54.919 --> 00:13:00.280
It gives us redundancy, and it allows us to handle high request loads.

00:13:00.280 --> 00:13:03.799
This also allows scaling.

00:13:03.799 --> 00:13:11.280
So in conclusion, I just want to show that R is great for production with proper CI and

00:13:11.280 --> 00:13:12.760
CD practices.

00:13:12.760 --> 00:13:16.760
Continuous integration helps you build and vet your R packages.

00:13:16.760 --> 00:13:22.520
Continuous deployment helps you release updates seamlessly.

00:13:22.520 --> 00:13:30.320
Plumber is an important component for a microservice, because it packages your R code behind an

00:13:30.320 --> 00:13:36.719
API, where any service that has no knowledge of R can get results from your R code.

00:13:36.719 --> 00:13:42.159
And then Docker creates these portable software packages that you can run on your laptop,

00:13:42.159 --> 00:13:43.799
you can run in the cloud.

00:13:43.799 --> 00:13:51.799
And then Kubernetes is essentially an orchestration engine that will take your dockerized application

00:13:51.799 --> 00:13:53.919
and run it in the cloud.

00:13:53.919 --> 00:13:59.599
It helps you maintain redundancy, it has health checks, it helps make sure that your application

00:13:59.599 --> 00:14:02.719
doesn't crash.

00:14:02.719 --> 00:14:05.960
And thank you.

00:14:05.960 --> 00:14:07.960
If anyone has some questions, I'd be happy to take them.

00:14:07.960 --> 00:14:09.960
Thank you.

00:14:09.960 --> 00:14:11.960
Thank you.

00:14:11.960 --> 00:14:13.960
Thank you.

00:14:13.960 --> 00:14:15.960
Thank you.

